Identity outliers

In boxplot, outliers are the values outside of the whiskers, which are the value greater than 1.5*IQR above the upper quartile or below the lower quartile. From the boxplot shown above, the varibale ‘ApplicantIncome’ has numerous outliers since it is clear to see that there are lots of points above the upper whisker.

4b. Are the results of both the plots comparable? Are there any differences in the two plots? What are the key differences?

The results of the boxplot and histogram for detecting extreme values and outliers in the 'applicant income' variable are comparable, but they offer different perspectives. Boxplot directly shows outliers as points outside the whiskers, making it easy to identify extreme values. Histogram highlights the frequency distribution of income values, with outliers appearing as isolated bars or bars with very low frequencies at the extremes.While both plots are useful for detecting extreme values and outliers, the boxplot is more direct and clear for outlier identification, whereas the histogram provides a detailed view of the data distribution.
